<br>
Wow--that's exactly right! For me anyway<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> . Besides the fact that it also strikes me as an act of revenge and is not applied fairly among ethnic groups even in the US, it is irrevocable. Even if there is a heaven, this should give pause to folks and it always amazes me when xians (whose savior was a victim of the death penalty poorly applied) favor this. I think jail is definitely in order and I'm not for parolling these guys, but killing them is not logical nor does it in any way solve the problem or act as an effective deterrent.<br>
<br>
Now I totally understand wanting your loved one's killer dead--that's a natural reaction and kudos to anyone who can overcome it, but we cannot base our justice system on the emotional desires of the victim. Society must take the higher path, ensure everyone's rights are honored and provide an avenue for which errors can be corrected or at least stopped.<br>
<br>
My 2 cents.<br>
