<br>
I think it is a penalty that is not uniformly applied, and the majority of people who are executed fall within the lowest income bracket.<br>
<br>
People have been executed or on death row and have been found to be innocent of the crime they are said to have commited.  That in itself is enough to question it's validity.<br>
<br>
The death penalty hasn't proven to be a deterrant to crime.  The example I'm thinking of is Canada, where they found violent crime actually went up after they reintroduced the death penalty - it was later repealed.<br>
<br>
Then again I think prison has become a little too cushy, it should be a punishment and not rec time.  I find it rather ironic that prisoners are given universal health care in the prison system, while there are millions of people who do not have adequate health care.<br>
<br>
