<br>
We hate to hear about jails being cushy, but it is easier to control prisoners and prevent riots if they can work out their energies (exercise, work) and numb their brains with TV or even improve them with books. It also gives the guards something they can take away for behavior modification. If it's all just crappy and miserable, what would be the point in behaving? I wouldn't want our prisons to be like turkish prisons where they just send you to rot. Let's face it, no matter how cushy the prison, it is still a complete loss of privacy, freedom and liberty.<br>
<br>
People on death row appeal endlessly (and who can blame them?), making death row more expensive than just housing them the rest of their natural lives. On the other hand, my heart is hardly bleeding for someone facing the death penalty, because they murdered someone and that someone did not get even a trial, a chance to say goodbye, or anything. The death row inmate has it a lot better than the person he murdered, IMO.<br>
<br>
Just my thoughts,<br>
DL <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jenterra>jenterra</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/8/03 10:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=51.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Death penalty</span><hr size=1> I am an atheist and I staunchly oppose the death penalty (though I do not view the two as inextricably linked).<br>
<br>
I agree with Stacy in that our judicial system should not be a vehicle for exacting revenge on behalf of the victims of crime.  I find the idea of &quot;closure&quot; a farce, and don't believe for one moment that anyone who's loved one died in the Oklahoma City bombing felt any less mournful the day after Timothy McVeigh was executed (though they may well have told themselves they did.)  George Orwell wrote a fabulous essay entitled, &quot;Revenge is Sour.&quot;  He forwards the idea that revenge - the &quot;romantic&quot; notions we've attached to our ideas of revenge, believing that it will be fulfilling, pleasurable, etc. -is an illusion.  I believe he is right.<br>
<br>
I don't see how we, as a civilized society, can deem the death penalty appropriate simply because it's cheaper to kill them than to incarcerate them.  <br>
<br>
I also agree with DL that maintaining a humane environment in prisons is important for a number of reasons -- I for one would hardly consider a stint in a maximum security facility a picnic, regardless of how often I got to work out, read, or educate myself.  And, since lack of education is at the root  of so much of what ails this country, I whole-heartedly support any effort even the most violent criminals might make toward improving their minds.  <br>
<br>
I see Leah's point:  that higher education isn't affordable and available to every citizen of the country is grossly outrageous.    But taking education out of prison reform is a step in the wrong direction.<br>
<br>
The bottom line, in my eyes, is that murder is murder.  We're supposed to be the good guys.<br>
<br>
Jen <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mormongirl2>Mormongirl2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 36<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/9/03 1:08 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=51.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   anti death penalty, pro-abortion</span><hr size=1> Maybe I should start this on another thread, but hey it 'sort of' deals with the OT.<br>
